n and model of development: urban-rural integration, tourism, and ecological civilization. Sorace’s work emphasizes the need for a grounded literacy in the political concepts, discourses, and vocabularies of the Communist Party itself. To dismiss China’s official discourse as "empty propaganda," Sorace argues, makes China and Chinese realities harder to understand, not easier.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aEarthquake reliefzChinazWenchuan Xian (Sichuan Sheng) 0aEarthquake reliefzChinazWenchuan Xian (Sichuan Sheng). 0aEmergency managementzChinazWenchuan Xian (Sichuan Sheng) 0aEmergency managementzChinazWenchuan Xian (Sichuan Sheng). 0aWenchuan Earthquake, China, 2008. 4aAsian Studies. 4aPolitical Science & Political History.  aChina, Sichuan earthquake, Communist Party, natural disaster, disaster response, disaster politics, contemporary Chinese politics, policymaking, political authority, political agenda, Chinese politics, Maoism, intellectual heritage of Maoism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Contemporary Collection eBook Packagez978311064982608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311066587140uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150170850340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501708503423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501708503/original  a978-3-11-064982-6  Asian Studies Contemporary Collection eBook Package  a978-3-11-066587-1  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles